    cellular: { title: "Impaired DNA Synthesis", content: "Macrocytic (megaloblastic) anemias result from impaired DNA synthesis, most commonly due to Vitamin B12 (cobalamin) or Folate (B9) deficiency. These vitamins are essential cofactors for nucleotide production. When deficient, cell division is delayed while cytoplasmic growth continues, resulting in abnormally large red blood cells (MCV >100 fL). In the bone marrow, this leads to 'megaloblastic' changes and ineffective erythropoiesis. B12 deficiency is unique because it also causes accumulation of methylmalonic acid (MMA), which damages the myelin sheath of nerves, leading to neurological symptoms (subacute combined degeneration). Folate deficiency does NOT cause neurological damage. A common cause of B12 deficiency is Pernicious Anemia, an autoimmune destruction of gastric parietal cells which produce intrinsic factor (IF), the protein required for B12 absorption in the terminal ileum." },
